{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> τοίνυν</b>, <br /> (τοι, νυν) <b>therefore, accordingly,</b> an inferential Particle (never in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus or 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus), χρὴ τ. πύλας ὕμνων ἀναπιτνάμεν 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 6.27, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; εἰ τ... [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.57 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἂν τ... [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 4.7 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; introducing a logical conclusion (less frequently than οὖν), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Charmides” 159d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; φανερὸν τ., δῆλον τ., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1260a2, “PA” 641a15 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; also to introduce a minor premiss, or a particular instance of a general proposition, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Cratylus” 399b, 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 4.103, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> in dialogue, to introduce an answer, <b>well</b> or <b>well then,</b> ἄπειμι τ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 1050, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 5.89, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; especially an answer which has been led up to by the same speaker, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Meno” 76a, “IG” 42(1).121.31 (Epid., 4th c.BC)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; in response to an invitation to speak, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 961, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; in expression of approval, especially in phrase καλῶς τ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Cratylus” 433a, etc.; κάλλιστα τ. 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 856 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also of disapproval or criticism, ἀπόλοιο τ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Nu.” 1236, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1067. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> continuing an argument, <b>well then,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 178d, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 3.1.36, 7.7.28, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <br /><Level4><b>__3.b</b></Level4> resuming the thread of argument or narrative after a break, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 562b, “Plt.” 275d, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 47.64, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <br /><Level4><b>__3.c</b></Level4> adding or passing to a fresh item or point, <b>further, moreover, again,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 33c, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 8.73, 20.18; ἔτι τ. 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ ἀρχαίης ἰητρικῇς” 19, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 109a, “Cri.” 52c, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 20.8; καὶ τ. 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 2.2.25; καί τ. καί 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Sophista” 234a \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; μὴ τ. μηδέ.. <b>nay,</b> not even.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 7.6.19; οὐ τ. οὐδέ \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<b>nor again,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ ἄρθρων ἐμβολῆς” 57, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 20.7. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> sometimes at the beginning of a speech, ἐγὼ μὲν τ..., referring to something present to the minds of the speaker and hearer, <b>now</b> I.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 5.1.2, compare “Cyr.” 6.2.14. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__5</b></Level3> with <i>subjunctive</i> of exhortation or <i>imperative</i>, in <i>significations</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1, 2, 3, εὖ τ. ἐπίστασθε.. [prev. author] “An.” 3.1.36, compare “Cyr.” 2.4.8, NT.Luke.20.25, etc. \">NT</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> Position: in early writers τοίνυν is never the first word in a sentence, but this is not uncommon in later authors, as [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.Isa.3.10, “Mim. Oxy.” 413.225, NT.Luke.20.25, NT.Heb.13.13, 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 2.526, 2nd c.AD: Sextus Empiricus Philosophus “adversus Mathematicos” 8.429, “Anthologia Graeca” 11.127 (2nd c.AD(?): Pollianus Epigrammaticus), “IG” 4.620.13 (from Argos), 6th c.AD: Choricius Rhetor 32.34\">LXX+NT+2nd c.AD+</a>] F.-R. codex (&lt;τῷ&gt; add. Kaibel); it is usually placed second, but sometimes later, ἥξω φέρουσα συμβολὰς τ. ἅμα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 143.1, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 863, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] [ῠ regularly, as [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 760, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 71 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: but sometimes ῡ, as [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 1259, 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor [same place]; in _anapaest meter_, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 429, 435, “Av.” 481.] \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5106","accentedUnicode":"τοίνυν","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G3568","matchingForm":"νῦν","stepTransliteration":"nun","gloss":"now","_zh_tw_Gloss":"現在","_es_Gloss":"ahora","_zh_Gloss":"现在"},{"strongNumber":"G5104","matchingForm":"τοί","stepTransliteration":"toi","gloss":"certainly","_zh_tw_Gloss":"只是","_es_Gloss":"ciertamente","_zh_Gloss":"只是"}],"shortDef":"then","mediumDef":"then <br />then, therefore, moreover","stepGloss":"then","stepTransliteration":"toinun","count":4,"_es_Definition":"luego, por lo tanto, entonces, por esa misma razon","_zh_tw_Definition":"因此, 之後, 那麼, 的確","_zh_Definition":"因此, 之后, 那么, 的确","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"thế thì; Vì thế","_zh_tw_Gloss":"這樣","_es_Gloss":"entonces","_zh_Gloss":"这样"}]}